rovides intimate portrayals of sex workers from sites including the Balkans, the Maghreb, and West Africa who decided to sell sex as the means to achieve a better life. Mai explores the contrast between how migrants understand themselves and their work and how humanitarian and governmental agencies conceal their stories, often unwittingly, by addressing them all as helpless victims. The culmination of two decades of research, Mobile Orientations sheds new light on the desires and ambitions of migrant sex workers across the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEurope-Emigration and immigration. 0aForeign workerszEurope. 0aForeign workers-Europe. 0aHuman traffickingzEurope. 0aHuman trafficking-Europe. 0aMale prostituteszEurope. 0aMale prostitutes-Europe. 0aMale prostitutionzEurope. 0aMale prostitution-Europe. 0aProstitutionzEurope. 0aProstitution-Europe. 0aSex workerszEurope. 0aSex workers-Europe. 0aSexual orientationzEurope. 0aSexual orientation-Europe. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aParticipatory methods.  aagency.  aautoethnography.  afilmmaking.  ahumanitarianism.  amigration.  aneoliberalism.  asex work.  atrafficking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226585147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226585147/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles